captions.text:
Solu: Don't, don't, that's not the way to
treat a friend.

COMM: Hand feeding a 1000 pound brown bear
may seem like a one-way ticket to an early

grave, but not for Sulo Karjalainen - known
in his native Finland as the Bear Man.

COMM: The 73-year-old runs Kuusamo Large Carnivore
Centre with his brother Jalo in the north

of the country, which has been home to more
than 20 orphaned brown bears.

COMM: After working on a research project
studying Finnish carnivores, Sulo was asked
if he would mind taking in some cubs.

COMM: And over the years a deep bond has grown
up between Sulo and his bears, meaning he's
even able to share a meal with them.

Sulo: Come on Juuso, have a taste. These are
good, aren't they?

COMM: The Fin, who has lived on the same farm
in Kuusamo all his life, has become a celebrity

in his homeland due to his incredible relationship
with the predators.

COMM: At present Sulo looks after six bears
and has no plans to retire any time soon.

Sulo: You're becoming a bad boy. Yes you are.
That's it buddy, see? All gone.

title: Bear Man Of Finland Has An Unbreakable Bond With Brown Bears
